Jose Carlos del Valle

Bio

Dr.Jos Carlos del Valle is a PhD in Biology that work at the University of Seville (Spain). His research has been mainly focused on the importance of non-pollinator mediated selection through the study of flavonoid accumulation in reproductive and vegetative tissues of plants and its implication for plant success in challenging ecosystems. Additionally, he has been conducting other research in others topics within the field of Evolutionary Biology, including the study of flower color polymorphism, population genetic and phylogeographic studies.

Education

Universidad Pablo de Olavide | Seville, Spain

Ph.D.in Biology | January 2014 - April 2018

Universidad de Sevilla | Seville, Spain

MS in Evolutionary Biology | September 2011 - October 2013

Universidad Pablo de Olavide | Seville, Spain

B.S. in Environmetal Sciences | September 2003 - July 2008

Experience

Postdoctoral researcher | Universidad de Seville (Spain)) | January 2021 - Present

Research support Technician | Universidad de Seville (Spain)) | November 2019 - December 2020

PhD Student | Universidad Pablo de Olavide (Spain) | January 2014 - December 2017

Research support Technician | Universidad Pablo de Olavide (Spain) | March 2013 - December 2013

Most recent publications

  • Major Flower Pigments Originate Different Colour Signals to Pollinators
  • Painting the green canvas: how pigments produce flower colours
  • The effects of pollination, herbivory and autonomous selfing on the maintenance of flower colour variation in Silene littorea
  • UV radiation increases phenolic compound protection but decreases reproduction in Silene littorea
